{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14875"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14875"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.17,0.66,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44541"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2907"},{"type":"tags","id":"2908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43564"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of decreased urine output and fatigue. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Heart sounds are normal and chest is clear. She has mild peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea 25 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine 350 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would most strongly suggest intrinsic renal disease rather than pre-renal acute kidney injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oliguria for more than 48 hours","Requirement for dialysis","Fractional excretion of sodium less than 1%","Dysmorphic red cells on urine microscopy","Creatinine greater than 400 \u03bcmol/L"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute kidney injury (AKI), which can be classified as pre-renal, intrinsic renal, or post-renal based on the underlying cause. Distinguishing between pre-renal and intrinsic renal causes is crucial for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysmorphic red cells\u003C/strong\u003E on urine microscopy strongly suggest glomerular damage, which is characteristic of intrinsic renal disease such as glomerulonephritis. The presence of red cell casts is particularly specific for glomerular injury. This finding helps differentiate intrinsic renal disease from pre-renal AKI, where the urine sediment is typically bland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreatinine greater than 400 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E indicates severe AKI but does not differentiate between pre-renal and intrinsic renal causes. The absolute creatinine value reflects the severity of kidney dysfunction rather than the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOliguria for more than 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in both pre-renal and intrinsic renal causes of AKI. The duration of oliguria alone cannot reliably distinguish between these causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erequirement for dialysis\u003C/strong\u003E indicates severe AKI but does not help determine the underlying cause. Both pre-renal and intrinsic renal causes can progress to require dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efractional excretion of sodium less than 1% \u003C/strong\u003Eis more likely to suggest pre-renal disease, but this test can be confounded by diuretic use and is less specific than urine microscopy findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther helpful distinguishing features include the clinical context and response to fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysmorphic red cells or red cell casts on urine microscopy suggest intrinsic renal disease rather than pre-renal acute kidney injury."],"references":["Goyal A, Daneshpajouhnejad P, Hashmi MF, Bashir K. Acute kidney injury (acute renal failure). In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441896/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14875"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44541"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T22:19:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T22:21:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"d